</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="133" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="133">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="133">
A Holarctic genus. The 26 European species are largely confined to higher altitudes. Twelve species are known from the Balkan Peninsula. Adults are well-known to visit flowers, where they feed on both nectar and pollen (
<bibRefCitation author="Pont, AC" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Natural History" pageId="13" pageNumber="144" pagination="631 - 643" title="Observations on anthophilous Muscidae and other Diptera (Insecta) in Abisko National Park, Sweden." url="10.1080/00222939300770361" volume="27" year="1993">Pont 1993</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae are terrestrial and are facultative to obligate carnivores (
<bibRefCitation author="Skidmore, P" journalOrPublisher="The biology of the Muscidae of the world (Series entomologica)" pageId="13" pageNumber="144" volume="29" year="1985">Skidmore 1985</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
